MTF,<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;Praising one's fighting men and women has been a standard<br>
practice for eons...I wonder why our society departed from such an important and meaningful display of recognition for its returning VietNam and Korean War veterans?  ....<br><br>
We must not lose sight of the fact that nobel brothers<br>
often give us recognition and respect.. the kind that really counts!&quot;<br><br>
It is funny, but I found a very early post of mine that expressed similar feelings, but back then, I wasn't really aware of the real impact the disconnect I experienced had upon me. I know now that the effects in part had far reaching consequences with my self esteem about my 'Nam experience. Trust issues and emotional difficulty in displaying my decorations or admitting that I was a Vietnam Veteran were some of the impacts. I have learned to compensate and move ahead, but at the core, it still really hurts. It probably always will. The amazing thing is that here I am talking about it, and not crashing! (today!)  That's progress! I know the support and insight I find here from you, Sparrowhawk, SW, Tom, Chet, and many others, has really helped, and I *really* appreciated that last scalp dance! I was honored, and it *counted*. <br><br>
I do not know what influence this part of things had on the course of my PTSD, but it surely did not help. It probably colorized the creature feature a little more. It is still a bitch. One day at a time! 
